WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.220
 So the last kind of events that we're going to talk about

00:00:02.220 --> 00:00:03.340
 are network events.

00:00:03.340 --> 00:00:06.540
 That is code that runs as your JavaScript

00:00:06.540 --> 00:00:08.800
 is talking to the network.

00:00:08.800 --> 00:00:11.140
 So we can do network operations in JavaScript.

00:00:11.140 --> 00:00:16.140
 We can do the entire request response cycle in JavaScript.

00:00:16.140 --> 00:00:22.240
 The problem is that this has to be an asynchronous process

00:00:22.240 --> 00:00:25.180
 because we can't pause our code.

00:00:25.180 --> 00:00:27.740
 We can't say stop and read from the server

00:00:27.740 --> 00:00:30.540
 because otherwise the browser would lock up.

00:00:30.540 --> 00:00:32.540
 So we have to kind of use events

00:00:32.540 --> 00:00:34.500
 and we kind of chain these events together.

00:00:34.500 --> 00:00:36.620
 We have a start the request

00:00:36.620 --> 00:00:40.660
 and then give me an event when the request is restarted

00:00:40.660 --> 00:00:43.500
 and then as the data is being retrieved,

00:00:43.500 --> 00:00:46.420
 when the data is all retrieved, then you process the request.

00:00:46.420 --> 00:00:49.720
 And so there's a multi-step process

00:00:49.720 --> 00:00:52.300
 and you do one step and then initiate the second step.

00:00:52.300 --> 00:00:56.220
 And so that means that we're never in our JavaScript

00:00:56.220 --> 00:00:57.980
 waiting for anything.

00:00:57.980 --> 00:01:01.780
 We are responding to an event

00:01:01.780 --> 00:01:03.180
 and then triggering another event

00:01:03.180 --> 00:01:04.420
 and then responding to an event

00:01:04.420 --> 00:01:05.820
 and triggering another event,

00:01:05.820 --> 00:01:10.020
 but never doing anything that waits in our code.

00:01:10.020 --> 00:01:13.420
 This particular code is 14-fetch.htm.

00:01:13.420 --> 00:01:17.500
 Now fetch is a function that's available

00:01:17.500 --> 00:01:19.180
 and its parameter is a URL.

00:01:19.180 --> 00:01:22.620
 So I've got this URL called secret.txt.

00:01:22.620 --> 00:01:25.900
 Now fetch returns what's called a promise.

00:01:25.900 --> 00:01:27.860
 A promise is something that hasn't happened yet,

00:01:27.860 --> 00:01:29.620
 but will happen.

00:01:29.620 --> 00:01:34.620
 And then you say .then and the then code runs

00:01:34.620 --> 00:01:37.380
 when the fetch has started.

00:01:37.380 --> 00:01:41.300
 And so in this case,

00:01:41.300 --> 00:01:43.180
 and I'm using this sort of short syntax

00:01:43.180 --> 00:01:46.560
 'cause this inside the parentheses of the then,

00:01:46.560 --> 00:01:49.020
 you see a function that takes a single parameter

00:01:49.020 --> 00:01:51.060
 as the variable response.

00:01:51.060 --> 00:01:53.220
 That's my choice as a variable name.

00:01:53.220 --> 00:01:57.420
 I console.log and then I return response.text.

00:01:57.420 --> 00:01:58.980
 Now what that really is saying

00:01:58.980 --> 00:02:02.100
 is now go retrieve that text,

00:02:02.100 --> 00:02:03.460
 which will take some time.

00:02:03.460 --> 00:02:07.260
 So response.text itself is another promise.

00:02:07.260 --> 00:02:11.160
 And so the return value of the first then

00:02:11.160 --> 00:02:12.500
 is itself a promise.

00:02:12.500 --> 00:02:14.880
 And that's why you see the second then.

00:02:14.880 --> 00:02:17.220
 Now the second then happens

00:02:17.220 --> 00:02:20.020
 when the response text has been retrieved

00:02:20.020 --> 00:02:23.820
 and now we're being handed that as a text string.

00:02:23.820 --> 00:02:26.040
 And then it says, let's run code

00:02:26.040 --> 00:02:27.740
 and console.log that text string.

00:02:27.740 --> 00:02:31.220
 So fetch starts and returns a promise,

00:02:31.220 --> 00:02:35.380
 then says when that promise completes, run this code,

00:02:35.380 --> 00:02:37.120
 and then return another promise.

00:02:37.120 --> 00:02:42.120
 And then the second then runs after the promise is retrieved

00:02:42.120 --> 00:02:44.320
 and then we're done.

00:02:44.320 --> 00:02:47.460
 So you see there's three little steps

00:02:47.460 --> 00:02:49.380
 and each of those steps is instantaneous

00:02:49.380 --> 00:02:50.620
 or as fast as we can do it.

00:02:50.620 --> 00:02:51.980
 And there's no waiting.

00:02:51.980 --> 00:02:55.020
 And each time we have to register a function

00:02:55.020 --> 00:02:57.300
 to respond to the request.

00:02:57.300 --> 00:03:03.460
 So JavaScript calls us back, okay?

00:03:03.460 --> 00:03:07.620
 And so you can kind of see this happen, right?

00:03:07.620 --> 00:03:12.000
 The fetch starts, the first promise resolves,

00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:14.620
 and we see what the response is.

00:03:14.620 --> 00:03:16.340
 Now if you look carefully,

00:03:16.340 --> 00:03:18.960
 you see that the response is a 200,

00:03:18.960 --> 00:03:21.500
 which means it looks like we're doing well, right?

00:03:21.500 --> 00:03:27.700
 And it has a readable stream,

00:03:27.700 --> 00:03:30.180
 but we have not yet used the body, okay?

00:03:30.180 --> 00:03:32.820
 So when it says body used equals false,

00:03:32.820 --> 00:03:35.460
 that means that we've sort of started the request

00:03:35.460 --> 00:03:37.100
 and it looks like it's gonna go well.

00:03:37.100 --> 00:03:39.700
 And now we're given a chance to see what we're going,

00:03:39.700 --> 00:03:41.520
 once this request has started.

00:03:41.520 --> 00:03:43.840
 Now by calling response.text,

00:03:43.840 --> 00:03:46.940
 that's a method inside this response object

00:03:46.940 --> 00:03:51.500
 that then says, oh, go back, make a new promise,

00:03:51.500 --> 00:03:52.980
 and that promise will be fulfilled

00:03:52.980 --> 00:03:54.600
 when we've actually retrieved the text.

00:03:54.600 --> 00:03:57.820
 So at this moment where it says console log response,

00:03:57.820 --> 00:03:59.900
 the text hasn't been retrieved yet,

00:03:59.900 --> 00:04:03.300
 and so we're returning a promise to be fulfilled

00:04:03.300 --> 00:04:05.380
 after the text is received.

00:04:05.380 --> 00:04:07.860
 Then when that text receiving is finished,

00:04:07.860 --> 00:04:10.580
 which might take two seconds or something,

00:04:10.580 --> 00:04:12.640
 then it's like, oh, I've got some text,

00:04:12.640 --> 00:04:16.260
 so I'm gonna call you back, resolve that promise,

00:04:16.260 --> 00:04:19.740
 and pass the actual retrieved text string back into us.

00:04:19.740 --> 00:04:22.140
 And so that's the only moment

00:04:22.140 --> 00:04:25.020
 that what the server has given for secret.txt,

00:04:25.020 --> 00:04:27.380
 which the secret of course is 42 is the text,

00:04:27.380 --> 00:04:29.860
 that's when we can actually print it out.

00:04:29.860 --> 00:04:32.600
 We can make this a little bit more succinct

00:04:32.600 --> 00:04:34.220
 and then watch it as it happens.

00:04:34.220 --> 00:04:37.240
 So this is 15-fetch.

00:04:37.240 --> 00:04:40.600
 So we're gonna do something with this text

00:04:40.600 --> 00:04:42.000
 instead of just printing it,

00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:45.420
 and we're gonna use kind of the more succinct

00:04:45.420 --> 00:04:48.180
 contraction style of this function code

00:04:48.180 --> 00:04:50.700
 and not put so many console logs in.

00:04:50.700 --> 00:04:51.780
 I was putting console logs

00:04:51.780 --> 00:04:53.860
 so you could see the steps that happen.

00:04:53.860 --> 00:04:56.120
 So this is a more typical way of doing something.

00:04:56.120 --> 00:04:58.220
 So we're gonna fetch secret.txt,

00:04:58.220 --> 00:04:59.700
 which is your on the server.

00:04:59.700 --> 00:05:03.660
 When that fetch has successfully started,

00:05:03.660 --> 00:05:08.000
 we resolve the first promise, and then we say, okay.

00:05:08.000 --> 00:05:10.500
 And the first response arrow response text,

00:05:10.500 --> 00:05:12.180
 response is the parameter to the function,

00:05:12.180 --> 00:05:14.660
 and response.text is calling the text method

00:05:14.660 --> 00:05:18.840
 in that, which is the return value to this first promise,

00:05:18.840 --> 00:05:21.940
 which is another promise, but that'll be it.

00:05:21.940 --> 00:05:25.540
 When that promise resolves, it'll resolve to a text string,

00:05:25.540 --> 00:05:28.820
 and that's where the second then says, take a variable.

00:05:28.820 --> 00:05:30.600
 Again, I could call text string x,

00:05:30.600 --> 00:05:32.260
 it's just a variable in a function call,

00:05:32.260 --> 00:05:34.340
 it's just a parameter in a function call.

00:05:34.340 --> 00:05:38.260
 So call me back, call me this function I'm making,

00:05:38.260 --> 00:05:42.900
 text string, and then get doc in that code

00:05:42.900 --> 00:05:45.820
 is document get element id by id zap,

00:05:45.820 --> 00:05:50.260
 which is that p tag, and I set its inner text

00:05:50.260 --> 00:05:53.140
 to be the text string that I retrieve from the server.

00:05:53.140 --> 00:05:57.720
 And so you can kind of see that we can do things,

00:05:57.720 --> 00:05:59.300
 we can get data from the server,

00:05:59.300 --> 00:06:01.700
 and then we can move it into our document object model.

00:06:01.700 --> 00:06:05.940
 And I tried to do this in the simplest and smallest version.

00:06:05.940 --> 00:06:08.660
 We will cover this in a lot more detail

00:06:08.660 --> 00:06:11.300
 when we actually have something more important to retrieve,

00:06:11.300 --> 00:06:14.440
 like JSON, for example, JavaScript Object Notation,

00:06:14.440 --> 00:06:16.320
 which is the next section.

00:06:16.320 --> 00:06:18.900
 (upbeat music)

